WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:17.270 --> 00:00:21.740
According to two studies, one done at the
Ataturk University in Turkey (in 1991) and

00:00:21.740 --> 00:00:26.770
another at the University of Manchester in
England (in 2006), both dogs and cats are

00:00:26.770 --> 00:00:28.830
typically right or left pawed.

00:00:28.830 --> 00:00:33.160
According to the Ataturk University study,
the majority of domestic cats are right pawed

00:00:33.160 --> 00:00:38.890
(50%), 10% of them are ambidextrous, and the
remaining 40% favor their left paw.

00:00:38.890 --> 00:00:42.650
Dogs, on the other hand, according to the
University of Manchester study, tend to be

00:00:42.650 --> 00:00:48.940
more evenly split with around 50% being left
pawed and 50% being right pawed, with a statistically

00:00:48.940 --> 00:00:51.930
insignificant number being ambidextrous.

00:00:51.930 --> 00:00:55.650
In addition to that, there seems to be a connection
between the gender of the animal and which

00:00:55.650 --> 00:00:58.350
paw is dominate in both cats and dogs.

00:00:58.350 --> 00:01:02.441
Specifically, female cats and dogs typically
will have their right paw be dominate, while

00:01:02.441 --> 00:01:04.270
males tend to go with the left paw.

00:01:04.270 --> 00:01:08.340
However, if the animal has been spayed or
neutered at an early age, this distinction

00:01:08.340 --> 00:01:09.780
goes away.

00:01:09.780 --> 00:01:13.730
Determining if your cat or dog is left or
right pawed or ambidextrous isn’t as simple

00:01:13.730 --> 00:01:17.780
as running one test, such as giving them a
toy to play with just out of their reach and

00:01:17.780 --> 00:01:19.900
seeing which paw they reach with.

00:01:19.900 --> 00:01:23.890
This is because their paw preference is often
weekly expressed, unlike with humans.

00:01:23.890 --> 00:01:27.870
Thus, in order to accurately determine your
pet’s paw preference, you need to run such

00:01:27.870 --> 00:01:31.200
tests several dozen times to see the trends.

00:01:31.200 --> 00:01:34.840
Some helpful such tests for dogs and cats
include: if you’ve taught your dog to shake

00:01:34.840 --> 00:01:37.539
hands, which paw do they seem to like to use
the most?

00:01:37.539 --> 00:01:41.440
If your dog or cat is playing on its back
and you put your hand just out of their reach,

00:01:41.440 --> 00:01:43.910
which paw do they reach for your hand with?

00:01:43.910 --> 00:01:48.400
You can also try putting a treat or a toy
just out of their reach underneath a bookshelf/coffee

00:01:48.400 --> 00:01:53.640
table/couch /etc. and see which paw they typically
try to reach for the treat or toy with.

00:01:53.640 --> 00:01:57.390
You can put some peanut butter on the top
center of their nose and see which paw they

00:01:57.390 --> 00:01:58.740
use to get it off with.

00:01:58.740 --> 00:02:03.720
For both dogs and cats, if the animal wants
inside or into a room you’re in, which paw

00:02:03.720 --> 00:02:06.069
do they typically use to scratch at the door?

00:02:06.069 --> 00:02:09.390
Another good one is to put a treat underneath
something and see which paw they use first

00:02:09.390 --> 00:02:11.280
to try to uncover the treat with.

00:02:11.280 --> 00:02:15.450
Yet another test is to place a small piece
of paper or plastic on a smooth surface so

00:02:15.450 --> 00:02:19.580
it can slide, and then place a tasty, lickable
treat on the paper.

00:02:19.580 --> 00:02:25.060
When the dog or cat licks it, inevitably the
paper/plastic will slide and they will likely

00:02:25.060 --> 00:02:28.470
use one of their paws to stop it from sliding
while they lick.

00:02:28.470 --> 00:02:32.750
In all these cases, record which paw is used
and once you’ve done several dozen such

00:02:32.750 --> 00:02:35.990
tests, check to see if there is a clear dominate
paw.

00:02:35.990 --> 00:02:38.340
If not, continue on until one emerges.

00:02:38.340 --> 00:02:43.260
If you’ve done 100-200 or so such tests
and there is no noticeable paw preference,

00:02:43.260 --> 00:02:45.160
your animal is probably ambidextrous.

00:02:45.160 --> 00:02:50.100
That being said, it should be noted that cats,
as in all things, tend to be trickier to figure

00:02:50.100 --> 00:02:51.320
out than dogs.

00:02:51.320 --> 00:02:55.530
For instance, it’s been observed that when
cats are playing, they typically don’t exhibit

00:02:55.530 --> 00:02:59.630
much in the way of paw preference, but when
they want something, like a treat, it’s

00:02:59.630 --> 00:03:04.150
then that they’ll usually use their dominant
paw first, unless they are simply one of those

00:03:04.150 --> 00:03:06.550
10% or so that are ambidextrous.

00:03:06.550 --> 00:03:09.680
Bonus Facts:
• Horses also can be left or right hoofed

00:03:09.680 --> 00:03:10.960
or ambidextrous.

00:03:10.960 --> 00:03:15.050
While for cats and dogs their paw preference
is fairly inconsequential, for race horses

00:03:15.050 --> 00:03:17.580
particularly, knowing this information can
be very important.

00:03:17.580 --> 00:03:22.230
For instance, in horse racing in America,
horses run counterclockwise and when turning,

00:03:22.230 --> 00:03:26.491
turn to the left, so which hoof is their dominate
can be important in that, “You have to work

00:03:26.491 --> 00:03:31.710
to get them to take the lead they prefer less,”
says Dr. Sharon Crowell-Davis at the College

00:03:31.710 --> 00:03:34.770
of Veterinary Medicine at the University of
Georgia.

00:03:34.770 --> 00:03:39.530
For courses where the horse has to turn multiple
ways, an ambidextrous horse then is more desirable

00:03:39.530 --> 00:03:43.629
than one who has a hoof preference.

